{"cursor":"3661","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox settlement |official_name = Bade Emirate |settlement_type = Nigerian\ntraditional state |pushpin_map = Nigeria |pushpin_map_caption =\n|coordinates_region = NG |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name =\n|subdivision_type1 = State |subdivision_name1 = Yobe State |population =\n|timezone = |utc_offset = |latd= 12|latm= 52|lats=5|latNS=N |longd= 11|longm=\n2|longs=47|longEW=E }} The 'Bade Emirate' is a traditional state with\nheadquarters in Gashua, Yobe State, Nigeria. Alhaji Abubakar Umar Suleiman is\nthe 11th Emir of Bade (Mai Bede), of the Bedde dynasty, turbaned on 12 November\n2005. {{cite web\n|url=http://news.biafranigeriaworld.com/archive/2005/11/14/index.html\n|title=Ibrahim swears in new emir in Yobe |work=BNW News |author=Njadvara Musa\n|date=November 14, 2005 |accessdate=2010-09-11}}\n\nThe Bade people are thought to have migrated to the area around 1300 CE, coming\naround the north of Lake Chad from Kanem. {{cite web |url=http://bade-\nemirate.com/ |title=ASSALAMU ALAIKUM (Welcome) |publisher=Bade Emirate council\n|accessdate=2010-09-11}} In 1808 the Bade, then subject to the Bornu\nEmpire, were attacked by Fulani jihad warriors, who were expanding their control\nacross Northern Nigeria. The emirate became independent in 1818 when Mai Lawan\nBabuje detached the Emirate from the Kanuri of Bornu and fortified Gorgorum as\nthe capital of an independent state. The state remained independent until the\nend of the century, when it fell to the Sudanese warrior Rabih az-Zubayr.\nFollowing Rabih's death, in 1902 the British confirmed the independence of the\nEmirate. {{cite book |pages=192â193 |title=Almanac of African peoples &\nnations |author=Muá¸¥ammad ZuhdÄ« Yakan |publisher=Transaction Publishers\n|year=1999 |ISBN=1-56000-433-9}}\n","linknr":126,"url":"Bade_Emirate","recorded":1375079880,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bade_Emirate&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bade_Emira